PCA for:

  • Dimensionality Reduction.
  • Independance of Variables

  • These variables are dependant.
  • Maybe only few variables will capture all information.

Hence, PCA.

Steps of PCA¶

  • Scaling
  • Covariance Matrix
  • Find Eigen Values and Eigen Vectors, hence principal component.
In [11]:
# Scaling for units removal
XScaled = X.apply(zscore)

Dimensionality Reduction¶

Now 3 dimensions seems very reasonable. With 3 variables we can explain over 95% of the variation in the original data!

In [20]:
pca3 = PCA(n_components=3) # use only top 3 features
pca3.fit(XScaled)
Out[20]:
PCA(n_components=3)
In [21]:
print(pca3.explained_variance_) # EIGEN VALUES

Fit Linear Model¶

Lets construct two linear models. The first with all the 6 independent variables and the second with only the 3 new variables constructed using PCA.

In [25]:
reg_model = LinearRegression()
reg_model.fit(XScaled,y)
reg_model.score(XScaled,y)
Out[25]:
0.8087079552406331
In [26]:
reg_model_pca = LinearRegression()
reg_model_pca.fit(Xpca3,y)
reg_model_pca.score(Xpca3,y)
Out[26]:
0.7799909620572006

Looks like by drop reducing dimensionality by 3, we only dropped around 3% in R^2! This is insample (on training data) and hence a drop in R^2 is expected. Still seems easy to justify the dropping of variables. An out of sample (on test data), with the 3 independent variables is likely to do better since that would be less of an over-fit.
